\begin_layout Title
A Prequel to the Space to Place Impact Evaluation - Assessing the Relative
 Importance of Space and Place Components 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
A pre-analysis plan 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Raising agricultural productivity among smallholder farmers in Sub-Saharan
 Africa is widely recognized as an important component of inclusive wealth
 creation and structural transformation.
 Central to this endeavor will be the adoption of sustainable soil and land
 management to improve the sustainability, resilience and productivity of
 agriculture.
 The USAID Bureau for Resilience and Food Security (RFS) has led a partnership
 with the International Fertilizer Development Center (IFDC) and other partners
 to build a low-cost 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Space to Place
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (S2P) approach for developing and disseminating localized fertilizer guidance.
 The S2P approach revolves around the delivery of spatially appropriate
 soil fertility management recommendations, guided by digitized soil maps
 (Space) combined with farm(er)-level characteristics (Place), for effective
 agronomic and fertilizer recommendations that increase fertilizer use efficienc
y to maintain or surpass current productivity levels, and reduce fertilizer
 wastage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IFPRI was tasked in 2023 to do a rigorous impact evaluation of the S2P approach.
 However, at the start of the project if quickly became clear that the S2P
 application was not going to be ready in the first operational year of
 the evaluation (during the 2024/25 growing season).
 A full and rigorous evaluation of the S2P approach was therefore deferred
 to the 2025/26 growing seasons and beyond.
 As such, we decided that  the 2024/25 growing season would be used to generate
 learning to inform S2P
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s theory of change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Governments in developing countries are trying to increase adoption of Green
 Revolution technologies, seed of improved varieties and mineral fertilizer
 in particular, through agricultural extension advice.
 In general, these extension systems provide blanket recommendations.
 One important reason why farmers fail to adopt a seemingly profitable yield
 improving technologies is heterogeneity in the farmer's ability and context.
 For instance, high transacting costs may make a technology unprofitable
 for a farmer even though on average the technology would be profitable
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "suri2011selection"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A similar argument can be made for the soil that the farmer works—another
 key production factor in agricultural production 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "arouna2021one"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Also here, differences in soil composition and nutrient content may mean
 that blanket fertilizer recommendations are sub-optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information and Communication Technologies (ICTs) may provide an opportunity
 to provide advisory services that are more tailored to the specific needs
 of farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "spielman2021information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Numerous Site Specific Fertilizer Recommendation Decision support tools
 have been developed with the promise to reduce inefficiencies coming from
 grossly simplified recommendations, thereby raising the productivity and
 profitability from adopting improved inputs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "arouna2021one"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, decision support tools for tailored nutrient recommendations have
 generally fallen short of expectations, and this is illustrated by the
 numerous apps and tools that are out there but fail to scale 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sida2023failure"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Some of the reasons why such tools do not have more impact may be related
 to the following open questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the issue of spatial resolution, or how site specific these tools really
 are.
 Many of the tools rely on models that predict soil composition in large
 areas.
 As such, it has been argued that, often, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

...the numerous laboratory services and digital applications providing field-specif
ic recommendations appear to promise more accuracy than soil analysis can
 realistically deliver
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "schut2020soil"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the tools often focus too much on in-field heterogeneity, but not socioeconomic
 heterogeneity of users 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sida2023failure"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is partly due to the fact that these tools are developed by agronomists
 who maximize yields.
 However, farmers typically base decisions on cost-benefit considerations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
related, the tools and apps we reviewed were mostly focusing on inorganic
 fertilizers.
 However, experts in the field were mostly talking about soil health.
 They argue that gains from using or re-optimizing inorganic fertilizer
 would be much smaller than what is typically found in on-station trials
 if we consider plots that suffer from years of nutrient mining and soil
 erosion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
decision support tools often take a host of pre-conditions for granted,
 the most critical probably being the fact that the recommended blend of
 soil macro- and micro nutrients is available to the farmer at reasonable
 cost.
 Indeed, as we will see below, most RCTs that study the effectiveness of
 DSTs have at least one treatment arm that investigates the importance of
 a particular pre-condition (such as access to insurance, finance or information
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Space2Place approach addresses some of these concerns by combining SPACE
 (top-down information) and PLACE (on-site information) in a singe decision
 support tool to develop practical, profitable, scale-appropriate fertilizer
 and land management recommendations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In light of this, we feel it is important to study the relative importance
 of the Space and Place components in a clean field experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Related literature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently, various studies have been done on site specific nutrient management
 recommendations.
 Below, we review some of the most relevant studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "beg2024information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is the only few study that has a treatment arm with a soil test (which
 is similar to one of our tretament arms, see below).
 In particular, they compare two types of variety-specific fertilizer recommenda
tions – government provided, community-level recommendations and plot-specific
 recommendations based on individual soil tests among rice farmers in Bangladesh.
 They find limited effects, except perhaps for a reduction in application
 error (difference between recommended quantity of a particular nutrient
 and quantity used).
 That is, some farmers were using more than the recommended TSP and as a
 result of the interention cut back.
 Some even appear to over-react and stop using TSP altoghether, leading
 to lower yield.
 They also find indications that farmers adapt seed use to match baseline
 fertilizer use.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gars2015confidence"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that plot-level soil testing and tailored input recommendations changed
 farmers’ fertilizer usage and increased the adoption of recommended practices,
 leading to improved yields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a different experiment, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1086/711174"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide farmers with a simple tool (a leaf color chart) and basic, rule-of-thum
b instructions to guide the timing and quantity of urea (nitrogen) application.
 This intervention with substantially lower mental and attention demands
 on farmers does have a significant effect on the quantity of urea (nitrogen-fer
tilizer) applied.
 Taken together, this led them to conclude that advice should be bundled
 with training and extension services to ensure farmers benefit as intended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "arouna2021one"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 evaluate the effectiveness of a mobile application that provides personalized
 advice on rice nutrient management in Nigeria.
 In particular, they evaluate RiceAdvice, an Android-based application to
 provide personalized recommendations on nutrient management (type, quantity,
 and timing of fertilizer) in rice production.They find that the intervention
 increases yields by 7 percent.
 No soil tests are done.
 They also have a treatment that combines personalized advice with a grant
 that provides the recommended level of fertilizer.
 Here they estimate a treatment effect of 20 percent.
 They found a 10% increase from the intervention on profit which increased
 to 23% when the intervention is combined with the grant.
 The mechanism behind the increase in yield and profitability seems to be
 a reallocation in the fertilizer mix, with farmers using less NPK and more
 Urea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ayalew2022site"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 evaluate the impact of targeted site-specific fertilizer blend recommendations
 to Ethiopian smallholder farmers on fertilizer usage, farm productivity,
 profits from maize production, and household welfare using a two-level
 cluster randomized control trial.
 They also have a treatment arm that adds insurance to the recommendation.
 They find significant reduction of the application error, which in turn
 affects yields.
 In particular, they report a 13 percent increase in yield (437 on baseline
 yield of 3250 kg/ha) and a very similar increase in farmer profit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "oyinbo2022digital"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 study maize in Nigeria.
 They study the impact of Site specific Soil Nutrient Management extension
 advice through the Nutrient Expert tool.
 They have two treatment arms and one business-as-usual blanket recommendations
 control.
 T1 farmers who are exposed to SSNM information interventions on nutrient
 application rates and fertilizer management, and T2 farmers who are exposed
 to the same SSNM information and additional information on the variability
 of expected returns to fertilizer investment under different price scenarios.
 They find modest effects on yields and profits.
 See also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "maertens2023sustainable"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Research Questions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our research aims to look at a prototype S2P intervention, as well as assess
 the relative importance of two of the key components.
 It will also investigate the role of resources constraints as a potential
 enabling factor.
 In particular, we look at the following research questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the provision of site-specific soil nutrient information and the recommenda
tion of a specific fertilizer blend based on this information, change outcomes
 of interest.
 The motivation for this research question can be found in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 component of S2P.
 It tests if providing objectively measured scientific information provided
 in a fairly top-down fashion suffices to instigate behavior change.
 The objective function in this research question is optimizing yield.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does providing advice based on farmer characteristics (farmer practices,
 budget constraints,...) and the environment in which farmer operates (availability
 of fertilizer, prices,...) changes outcomes of interest.
 This research question speaks to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Place
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 component of S2P.
 The objective function in this research question is profit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the provision of site-specific nutrient information and farm-specific
 and farmer-tailored agronomic information with respect to soil nutrient
 management change outcomes of interest.
 This research question focuses on potential interactions between the Space
 and Place components as implied in the S2P approach.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the provision of site-specific nutrient recommendations and agronomic
 information with respect to soil nutrient management, combined with a subsidy
 to buy these nutrients at a local agro-dealer change the outcomes of interest.
 This research question looks at the importance of cash/credit constraints
 in the effectiveness of S2P.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sample and external validity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The study area requires on the one hand the presence of Meridian
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s agro-dealers (to ensure availability of the recommended inputs and to
 run the voucher scheme through), but on the other hand a population that
 has not yet been exposed to FSU
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s soil testing and nutrient recommendation system.
 We intend to work with FSU to identify greenfield locations, where FSU
 is currently not operational, but where it is considering expansion by
 setting up new agro-dealerships.
 We would then work with FSU to adapt their approach in these areas for
 2024/25 season only.
 Within the market shed of the new shop, we will select X villages and compile
 a list all farmers with at least 0.4 ha of land.
 From this list we will randomly assign farmers into the 5 different treatment
 groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
AIP recipients 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are expecting about one out of every four farmers in our sample to be
 receiving an AIP subsidy for the purchase of 50kg of the standard NPK blend
 and 50kg of Urea.
 The prevalence of AIP recipients will be balanced across treatment and
 control (that is, we will block on being an AIP recipient in some way).
 This will also allow us to look at treatment heterogeneity of the intervention
 on this attribute (impact of interventions among AIP recipient versus impact
 of interventions among non-AIP recipient) - see next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Impact heterogeneity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will study heterogeneity across gender, land size, wealth, remoteness,
 availability of labor in the household, receipt of an AIP subsidy, and
 use of improved agricultural technology (irrigation, improved seeds, soil
 health management,…).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Treatment Protocols 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 1 (T1): In a first treatment, a maize farmer is offered a free
 soil test on their main plot.
 If they accept, a few days later the farmer receives a soil report (see
 example in Appendix 1), with some key characteristics of the soil.
 The report indicates the soil
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s texture, pH level, cation exchange capacity, percentage organic matter,
 total nitrogen, carbon to nitrogen ratio, as well as the parts per million
 of available P, exchangeable K, calcium, magnesium, iron, manganese, boron,
 copper and zinc.
 Beyond the exact measurements each soil property is given a score on a
 4-point Likert scale (very low, low, high, very high), with emojis, color
 coding and bar charts indicating where the soil is deficient and where
 the levels are sound.
 Using a script, an enumerator then discusses the soil report with the farmer
 to derive a recommended nutrient package specific to the crop the farmer
 wants to grow.
 The farmer is then informed where and how to obtain these nutrients.
 The philosophy behind this treatment is really to provide objective information
 about the soil on the plot that was chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For this treatment, we cooperate with Meridian's Farmer Support Unit (FSU).
 This private-sector player offers farmers spectral soil tests and site-
 and crop-specific recommendations.
 The model underlying the test was calibrated on wet-chemistry analyses
 conducted on 22,000 samples from across Malawi and has been rolled out
 across X years, now reaching Y farmers.
 The tool is part of a private-sector business model in which FSU Meridian
 forms a recommendation for a package of nutrients, which is then supplied
 through their network of 400 agrodealers.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 2 (T2): using a simple application (fertilizer optimizer), data
 is collected on inorganic fertilizer application that the farmer is planning
 to use in the upcoming season.
 It asks at what prices the farmer can obtain these fertilizers, and what
 the farmer plans to spend in total on fertilizers.
 It also allows one to input soil nutrient management practices that the
 farmer will use and has used in the past.
 This information is then used to come up with tailor-made suggestions on
 how the farmer can optimize fertilizer use.
 The philosophy behind this treatment is on the economics behind decision
 making related to inorganic fertilizer use.
 More information on the fertilizer optimizer app can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wortmann2017fertilizer"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 3: (T3): This treatment combines treatments T1 and T2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 4 (T4): a voucher to buy the recommended nutrients at a local
 agro-dealer.
 The voucher will be of a value equivalent to the government
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s fertilizer subsidy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Comparison (C): A pure control with no soil test, no custom recommendations
 on optimal soil fertility management, and no subsidy.
 They will only provided with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blanket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 recommendation of the three most important practices that can be used to
 improve soil health.
\end_layout

